{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d209538a-6dbb-4050-b4e5-fb5095be97bf","content":"This is a known breaking change in .NET's crypto evolution. Here's what happened:\n\n## What changed\n\n`DSA.Create()` throws **`PlatformNotSupportedException`** on macOS in .NET 11. macOS's native Security framework (SecKey) has **never** supported DSA — in earlier .NET versions, the runtime silently fell back to an OpenSSL shim (`libssl`). .NET 11 removed that fallback, aligning macOS with the `SYSLIB0024` obsoletion that's been warning since .NET 7.\n\n## How to fix it\n\nSince you only need to **verify** existing legacy signatures (not generate new ones), use a managed DSA implementation like **BouncyCastle**:\n\n```bash\ndotnet add package BouncyCastle.Cryptography\n```\n\nThen replace the platform-dependent call:\n\n```csharp\n// ❌ Before — throws on macOS (.NET 11+)\nusing var dsa = DSA.Create();\ndsa.ImportSubjectPublicKeyInfo(publicKeyBytes, out _);\nbool valid = dsa.VerifyData(data, signature, HashAlgorithmName.SHA1);\n\n// ✅ After — managed, cross-platform\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Parameters;\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Security;\n\nvar pubKey = PublicKeyFactory.CreateKey(publicKeyBytes);\nvar verifier = SignerUtilities.GetSigner(\"SHA1withDSA\");\nverifier.Init(forSigning: false, pubKey);\nverifier.BlockUpdate(data, 0, data.Length);\nbool valid = verifier.VerifySignature(signature);\n```\n\n## Longer term\n\nMigrate away from DSA entirely — it's capped at 1024-bit keys in FIPS 186-2 and is considered legacy. RSA or ECDSA are the recommended replacements. If you control both signer and verifier, re-sign with a modern algorithm.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"dd537b21-762a-42bb-8d06-6bf96893e01a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET compatibility issue with DSA (Digital Signature Algorithm) on macOS after upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11. Let me think about what I know about this topic.\n\nThis is a well-known breaking change in .NET. Starting with .NET 7, Microsoft began deprecating older cryptographic algorithms, and DSA specifically has been affected on macOS.\n\nHere's what happened:\n\nIn .NET 7+, Apple's Security framework (which .NET uses on macOS) dropped support for DSA. The `DSA.Create()` method throws a `PlatformNotSupportedException` on macOS because the underlying native crypto library (Apple's CommonCrypto/Security framework) no longer supports DSA.\n\n\nThe deprecation started with attributes marking DSA as unsupported on certain platforms, and macOS eventually became one of them. I should be careful about the exact timeline though—the user mentioned upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11, which would be recent versions, so the issue they're hitting is likely the culmination of these changes that started back in .NET 7. macOS never had native DSA support through Apple's frameworks, so .NET historically relied on OpenSSL via Homebrew for DSA operations. Microsoft has been phasing out legacy crypto algorithms, so the breaking change in .NET 11 is likely that DSA.Create() now throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on macOS because they removed the OpenSSL backend or explicitly marked macOS as unsupported for DSA. So in .NET 11, DSA support was completely removed on macOS since the platform's native Security framework doesn't support it and Microsoft dropped the OpenSSL fallback. For verification of existing DSA signatures, I could use BouncyCastle's managed implementation or call OpenSSL directly, though ideally migrating away from DSA altogether would be the best path forward.","outputTokens":1811,"requestId":"A46B:F4466:2361BA4:271FE34:6A03D969"},"id":"de02937f-f413-4205-b3b6-a75397c2f1cd","timestamp":"2026-05-13T01:53:20.932Z","parentId":"3bea2118-3478-44da-99d1-0264ab695848"}
